    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-10-18T21:13:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-10-18T21:13:00-05:00" n="576"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d576">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.50/68: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Vladivostok</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MDB1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Macgowan</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Vladivostok</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-10-19T11:00:00+08:47">
                            <hi rend="italic">October 19, 1919, 11 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received 5:19 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>555. …</p>
                <p>I had opportunity yesterday to confer with all representatives of the United
                    States here and all agreed on the following points.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Political conditions eastern Siberia quieter than for months, possibly a
                        year.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>There is no danger whatever of Cossacks now attacking Americans or seizing
                        Chinese Eastern railway.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Anti-American propaganda has been decreased for some time and there is
                        evidence of more critical attention of Japanese [<hi rend="italic"
                        >sic</hi>].</item>
                    <pb facs="0645" n="533" xml:id="pg_533"/>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>Organized opposition and plotting against <persName corresp="#p_KAAV1"
                            >Kolchak</persName> is no longer heard of. I attribute 4 in large
                        measure to the Department telegrams Oct. 2, 6 p.m.<note n="78"
                            xml:id="d576fn78">
                            <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_437">p. 437</ref>.</note>
                        and Oct. 8, 6 p.m. [<hi rend="italic">October 7, 2 p.m.?</hi>].<note n="79"
                            xml:id="d576fn79">
                            <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_439">p. 439</ref>.</note>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>If I may venture an opinion, the foregoing and favorable news from all fronts
                    afford an opportunity for the United States to express in action its sympathy
                    and support of a united, democratic Russia represented by <persName
                        corresp="#p_KAAV1">Kolchak</persName>. His failure might result in break up
                    Russia into military states under foreign domination and permanent occupation
                    eastern Siberia by Japan which may be nearer <hi rend="italic">fait
                        accompli</hi> than is supposed . . . .</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MDB1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Macgowan</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
